    "answers": [{
        "owner": {
            "profile_image": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-caQ1VdKoE_I/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAFHE/etCbxnBDu7k/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
            "account_id": 7677535,
            "user_type": "registered",
            "user_id": 5817888,
            "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5817888/j%c3%a9r%c3%a9mie-b",
            "reputation": 11032,
            "display_name": "J&#233;r&#233;mie B",
            "accept_rate": 33
        },
        "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
        "score": 5,
        "is_accepted": true,
        "last_activity_date": 1455299042,
        "creation_date": 1455299042,
        "body": "<p>unfortunaly, the limit of <code>wrapper.java.maxmemory<\/code> is hardcoded in the version used in Karaf (wrapper.c, v3.2.3) :<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>/* Maximum JVM memory */\nmaxMemory = getIntProperty(properties, \"wrapper.java.maxmemory\", 0);\nif (maxMemory &gt; 0) {\n    maxMemory = __min(__max(maxMemory, initMemory), 4096);  /* initMemory &lt;= n &lt;= 4096 */\n    if (strings) {\n        strings[index] = malloc(sizeof(char) * (5 + 4 + 1));  /* Allow up to 4 digits. */\n        sprintf(strings[index], \"-Xmx%dm\", maxMemory);\n    }\n    index++;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>You should use something like <code>wrapper.java.additional.1 = -Xmx8196m<\/code><\/p>\n",
        "answer_id": 35369004,
        "question_id": 35368821
    }],
